  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe given reproducer shows
Correlated Value Propagation (CVP) adding nuw/nsw flags to a trunc instruction:\n
%conv = trunc i16 %or to i8\nwhich subsequently leads to Alive2 finding a
miscompile: For x=128, %or=129, the original program produces 0x81 (-127), but
the transformed program marks the trunc as nuw nsw, making it poison when the
source value does not fit the destination, thus causing UB. This is a clear
\"source more defined than target\" violation.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe
opt --passes=correlated-propagation output shows:\n- The function return gets a
range(i8 -128, 1) attribute.\n- The trunc gains both nuw and nsw flags.\nThese
are the first observable transformations. The miscompile is triggered by the
addition of nuw/nsw to trunc.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn CVP, processTrunc
sets no-unsigned-wrap and no-signed-wrap on trunc based on LazyValueInfo
ranges:\n  - NUW if Range.getActiveBits() <= DestWidth\n  - NSW if
Range.getMinSignedBits() <= DestWidth\nThis assumes LVI can prove that the source
value always fits in the destination width. However, in the reproducer, %or = %x
| 1 can be 129 when %x=128, which does not fit in i8 signed range and exceeds
unsigned maximum for some cases; adding nuw/nsw is incorrect. The LVI range used
at the trunc use point appears overly optimistic or not globally valid, leading
CVP to mark trunc as nuw/nsw even though values outside the i8 range are
possible. With trunc, nuw/nsw introduce a poison-on-out-of-range semantics that
was not present originally, making the transformation non-equivalent.\nGiven the
high risk and the subtlety of proving globally that a value always fits into a
smaller integer type under all paths, processTrunc's current criteria are
insufficiently conservative and can misfire as observed.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s)\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/CorrelatedValuePropagation.cpp\n-
Lines: 1215-1240\n- Change: Disable or tighten the deduction of nuw/nsw flags on
trunc. The safest immediate fix is to stop setting these flags entirely in CVP to
avoid introducing poison semantics erroneously. Specifically, modify processTrunc
to simply return false (i.e., perform no changes), or guard deductions with a
strictly stronger proof. For now, remove the block that sets
HasNoUnsignedWrap/HasNoSignedWrap based on Range and return false.\n\nSuggested
patch (conceptual):\n  static bool processTrunc(TruncInst *TI, LazyValueInfo
*LVI) {\n    // Do not deduce NUW/NSW for trunc here; current criteria can be
unsound\n    // and introduce poison when values do not fit the destination
type.\n    return false;\n  }\n\nAlternatively, if we prefer to keep the function
shape and stats but avoid mutations:\n  - Keep the function but remove the logic
that calls TI->setHasNoUnsignedWrap and TI->setHasNoSignedWrap; just compute
Range and return false.\n\nRationale: Adding nuw/nsw to trunc changes semantics
to require that the source always fits into the destination type, which is not
guaranteed by the observed LVI results and leads to UB in the provided
case.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe incorrect addition of nuw/nsw flags on trunc in CVP
is the root cause. By disabling the processTrunc deduction of no-wrap flags, we
prevent introduction of poison semantics and restore correctness. This avoids the
Alive2 failure and ensures CVP remains conservative when dealing with trunc
casts, which are particularly sensitive to poison semantics. If we later want to
reintroduce such deductions, they must be backed by stronger global guarantees
(e.g., proven range constraints invariant across all paths) and careful handling
of poison/undef considerations.",
